## Quick Start

Install all skills:

```bash
npx skills@latest add {{REPO_SLUG}}
```

Install a specific skill:

```bash
npx skills@latest add {{REPO_SLUG}} --skill <name>
```

Install for a specific agent:

```bash
npx skills@latest add {{REPO_SLUG}} --agent claude-code cursor
```

Install globally (available in all projects):

```bash
npx skills@latest add {{REPO_SLUG}} -g
```

## Available Skills

_No skills yet. Skills are added one directory at a time. Each skill lives at the repo root as `<skill-slug>/SKILL.md` (plus optional `README.md` and companion files), and is also surfaced in `docs/site.js` so it shows up on the Pages site._

## What Are Skills?

Skills are self-contained units of functionality that teach AI coding agents how to perform specific tasks. Each skill is a `SKILL.md` file (with optional companion files) that gets loaded into the agent's context when invoked.

Skills can be invoked by name (e.g., `/tdd`, `/prd-draft`) or automatically triggered by the agent when relevant.

## Manual Installation

If you prefer not to use the CLI, copy skill directories into your agent's skills folder:

| Agent | Project Path | Global Path |
|-------|--------------|-------------|
| Devin / Windsurf | `.cognition/skills/` or `.windsurf/skills/` | `~/.config/cognition/skills/` |
| Claude Code | `.claude/skills/` | `~/.claude/skills/` |
| Cursor | `.cursor/skills/` | — |
| Codex | Append to `AGENTS.md` | — |
| Gemini CLI | Append to `GEMINI.md` | — |

## Adding a New Skill

1. Create a directory `<skill-slug>/` at the repo root with at minimum a `SKILL.md` (frontmatter + body).
2. Add an entry to the `skills` array in [`docs/site.js`](./docs/site.js) — `slug`, `name`, `category`, `tagline`, `detail`, `usage`.
3. Append a dated entry to the `changes` array in `docs/site.js` and to [`CHANGELOG.md`](./CHANGELOG.md).
4. Add the skill row to the **Available Skills** table above.
5. Open a PR to `main`.

The GitHub Pages site rebuilds automatically on push to `main`.

## Docs site

The Pages site under `docs/` is a static HTML/CSS/JS scaffold (no Jekyll). It reads its data from the `skills` and `changes` arrays in `docs/site.js`.
